# Mechanical Behavior of Crosslinked Network Materials

Based on their mechanical behavior, network materials can be divided in three classes – see Fig. 3. Materials from class A are brittle and have an approximately linear stress-strain curve up to or close to failure. Materials of class B have a concave stress-strain curve, with a yield-point which typically separates the elastic and plastic regions of the curve. Materials of class C are hyperelastic, stiffen continuously as they are stretched and follow the loading path during unloading (some degree of hysteresis is possible). 

In compression, some network materials exhibit softening, followed by stiffening at large strains, as shown in Fig. 3. Other network materials which are embedded in a volume preserving matrix (e.g. hydrogels), exhibit less softening. 

